The Turing Test#Newline is a test to see if a computer can trick a person into believing that the computer is a person too. the Turing test interested

the Turing Test interested#Newline
  • The Turing test was introduced by Alan Turing in his 1950 paper Computing Machinery and Intelligence#Comma which opens with the words: "I propose to consider the question#Comma 'Can machines think?'"
  • Turing himself did not explicitly state that the Turing test could be used as a measure of intelligence#Comma or any other human quality.
  • In practice#Comma the Turing test's results can easily be dominated not by the computer's intelligence#Comma but by the attitudes and skill of the questioner.
  • Mainstream AI researchers argue that trying to pass the Turing Test is merely a distraction from more fruitful research.
  • Turing predicted that machines would eventually be able to pass the test; in fact#Comma he estimated that by the year 2000#Comma machines with approximately 120 megabytes of memory would be able to fool thirty percent of human judges in a five-minute test.
